        {
          "question": "Can my parent keep their house if it's worth more than the asset limit?",
          "answer": "Yes. The primary home is completely exempt regardless of value. Only the asset limits of $9,090 (single) or $13,630 (couple) apply to countable assets like bank accounts, investments, and additional vehicles."
        },
        {
          "question": "What's the difference between the three MSP tiers my parent might qualify for?",
          "answer": "QMB (lowest income) covers all Medicare premiums, deductibles, and coinsurance. SLMB covers only Medicare Part B premiums ($174.70/month in 2025). QI also covers Part B premiums but has limited federal funding and may not be available year-round."
        },
        {
          "question": "Will my parent get a Medicaid card if they're approved for MSP?",
          "answer": "Only QMB recipients receive a gray and white Medicaid card. SLMB and QI recipients get a determination letter confirming that their Medicare premiums are being paid, but no physical card."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for MSP on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "Yes, but you'll need legal authorization such as power of attorney or guardianship documents. The local Department of Social Services can guide you through the representative application process."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my parent's income changes after they're approved?",
          "answer": "Report income changes to your local Department of Social Services within 30 days. Increases might affect eligibility, while decreases could qualify your parent for a higher tier of benefits with more coverage."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent have MSP and also apply for other programs like SNAP?",
          "answer": "Yes. MSP eligibility often makes your parent automatically eligible for SNAP and other benefits. The Department of Social Services will screen for all available programs during the application process."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long does MSP coverage last once approved?",
          "answer": "MSP coverage continues as long as your parent remains eligible. Maryland conducts periodic reviews (typically annually) to confirm continued eligibility based on income and asset limits."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent is paying Medicare premiums now — will they get reimbursed?",
          "answer": "SLMB and QI coverage can be retroactive up to 3 months before the application date, meaning Medicare premiums paid during that period may be refunded. QMB retroactivity rules vary."
        }
