      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my parent keep their house and still qualify for SNAP?",
          "answer": "Yes, home value is completely exempt from SNAP asset limits. Your parent can own a home worth any amount and still qualify as long as their other countable assets (bank accounts, non-retirement investments) stay under $3,001 for households with members 60+."
        },
        {
          "question": "Do Social Security and pension payments count against the income limit?",
          "answer": "Yes, Social Security benefits, pensions, and disability income all count toward the $2,152/month income limit for single seniors. However, medical expenses over $35/month are deductible from income, which can help you qualify or increase benefits."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent lives with family but buys their own groceries?",
          "answer": "SNAP looks at who buys and prepares food together, not just who lives together. If your parent shops separately and prepares their own meals, they can apply as a separate household of one. If they share meals or grocery shopping, the whole household must apply together."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SNAP on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can apply as an authorized representative for your parent, but you'll need to provide documentation of your authority to act on their behalf (power of attorney, guardianship papers, or signed authorization). Your parent or you will still need to complete the required interview."
        },
        {
          "question": "What medical expenses can reduce my parent's countable income?",
          "answer": "Medical expenses over $35/month are deductible for those 60+, including Medicare premiums, prescription costs, doctor visits, dental care, eyeglasses, and medical equipment. Keep receipts from the last 3 months — this deduction often makes the difference between qualifying or not."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent use SNAP benefits at farmers markets?",
          "answer": "Yes, the EBT card works at participating farmers markets throughout Maryland. Many markets also offer matching programs that double your SNAP dollars when buying fresh fruits and vegetables, effectively increasing your buying power."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens to SNAP benefits if my parent moves to assisted living?",
          "answer": "If your parent moves to an assisted living facility that provides meals, they may no longer be eligible for SNAP since they're not buying and preparing their own food. However, if they have a kitchenette and buy their own groceries, they can continue receiving benefits."
        },
        {
          "question": "How often does my parent need to renew their SNAP benefits?",
          "answer": "Most SNAP recipients must renew every 12 months, but some seniors may qualify for 24-month certification periods if they have fixed income and no able-bodied adults in the household. You'll receive renewal notices by mail with specific deadlines and required documentation."
        }
      ],
